===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ar|en}} {{term|مُسْلِمٌ||one who submits|tr=múslim<sup>un</sup>|lang=ar}}, the active {{w|Arabic grammar#Participle|participle}}<ref>also known as an "infinitive", compare Burns & Ralph, ''World Civilizations'', 5th ed., p. 371</ref> of {{term|أسْلَمَ||he submitted|tr=ʾáslama|lang=ar}}, [[Appendix:Arabic verb forms#Form IV|verb form IV]] from the [[triliteral]] root {{ar-root|س|ل|م}}, "to be whole, intact". The verbal noun {{term|إسْلامٌ|lang=ar|tr=ʾislām<sup>un</sup>}} means literally "submission". In a religious sense, ''{{w|Islam|al-Islām}}'' translates to "faith, piety", and ''Muslim'' to "one who has (religious) faith or piety".

